In Need for Speed: The Run is racing across America.
Reviews
Originally a carefree ride turns into a routine morning shift due to a series of completely useless sloppy mistakes.
The ambition has been largely achieved, but it is not valid if no one was clearly willing to do anything extra.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run woke up before issuing high expectations.
He promised that the years-old race series Need for Speed would move again a bit in a new direction and from playable pointers he appeared as a game that might not be just in numbers in the genre of action racing.
We were also wondering what would happen to the embedded passages in which the main hero would step out of the car and take place on his own.
But as the NFS series is a habit, many of them are a little different than we expected.
They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down several unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less several years.
So it's actually not even mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of developers.
Adventure begins very well.
You're in a story whose lead hero Jack has certain personal issues and offers to participate in an illegal race across America as a solution.
You will take the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
The idea carries several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is driven on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't feel like you're offering the same thing for a second.
Some of the environments are also very pretty to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous works of the series.
So it's not a world-class thing.
But driving across the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snow mountains seems visually very pleasant.
Moreover, from time to time, the races are enhanced by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get tangled up in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to be buried in an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well placed behind each other.
There are only a few types, but it's enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the desired number of opponents (basically a classic race), then make up time again (classic stop fight), and then there's a duel with a single opponent waiting for you.
The police will also get involved from time to time, which makes your efforts even more difficult.
The news is the passages outside the wagon.
It's more of an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
But it is surprising that these passages are much less in play than you would expect (perhaps even three).
In the end, however, this is to the benefit of the matter, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the above mentioned, it is one of the elements that will enhance the game.
The model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is certainly not something these days, but it cannot be said to be a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the more active racing of the local driving model still suits quite well, even though we could find a better one for the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
But problems start to appear after a while.
Unlike the model of the road, the collision model is no longer in order.
We do not expect this type of game to calculate complex distortions and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave before any impact on any object, then everything is probably not quite right.
Typically, when passing or passing cars in normal traffic, you only lick each other slightly, but sometimes in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even just blow it up.
Thanks to the reboot system, it doesn't matter, but it's going to upset you reliably.
The restarts are dealt with so that if you smash yourself or drive far off the track, the game will throw you back at the last catch point on the track.
But only five restarts are available in each race.
If you wear them out, you have to start the race all over again.
So it's more of a tool in case something goes wrong than you could rely on them specifically.
But sometimes restarts don't help, they are solved by the need to learn the part of the race from memory.
The great ailment of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some corners need to be passed in a specific way, otherwise you just can't fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civilian" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It will upset you especially in situations where you can see your opponent passing in front of you easily between two anti-driving cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you get there, because it's "calculated" so that the situation always happens right under your nose.
The competition has another advantage.
During the whole game you will find several places where once again, regardless of the time, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the long bridge game, where you're going in the opposite direction.
Apparently, an opponent has to get there in front of you at any price.
When he's driving in front of you, he's making your mind up about the anti-driving cars, so you're probably going to break up in there a couple of times at first.
You can understand the intention of making the game more exciting and adrenalin-like, but the execution is so obvious that it reliably quickly disgusts you.
And it's a shame, because despite a simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes so action that sometimes you literally can't keep track of where things fly.
And it doesn't really matter whether it's a concept with 50 unique tracks, a race shift so that boredom doesn't stand a chance, or anything else.
The unconventional idea is to switch cars during races.
You have to keep an eye on the petrol pumps on the roads, because that's where you can change the car, even though in the vast majority of cases you can make do with what you have right now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars on straight highways and exotic supersports for technical driving, for example on winding mountain paths.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and mode challenges, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common to challenges and stories.
Different items are unlocked to obtain a higher level of driver: starting with cars and ending with background for profile.
He is also reconnected with the online Autologg feature, which, among other things, compares your achieved results with other players and provides other community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can reach the subway tunnel (be it), where you take it in the dark on the tracks (be it).
The numbers are flashing between 150 and 200 km / h (be it) on the speedometer, and the subway set comes in from behind, and you are uncompromising.
In the editorial room, we will probably still have a few days to discuss whether nobody really thought a little bit about it or whether the authors think we're really such a big jerk.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in several cases even great.
It is unfortunate that in some of the more tense moments, the imaging is falling rather tragically in some cases.
This is mainly about accidents with a larger number of participants, where continuous imaging would be of no use to you anyway.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category "every dog of another village" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, someone probably won't buy the game.
General Impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so highly self-conscious.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS work in the last few years.
But this is how the game looks unfinished.
I'm sure the fun is fine, but get ready for the mistakes to hit you in the eye with the power of airport lights.
