History of IBM: From Cheese Slice to Space
IBM (International Business Machinery) was established in New York a hundred years ago, originally having a complex name for Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was taken over only in 1924 - originally it was a brand used for branches in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as the famous "fuck-ups," i.e. hours recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board of the company until 1930.
Flint hired the head of the rival firm Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - the invincible corporate culture and identity are still built on Watson's ideas.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began to produce and sell all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson was running the company, the turnover doubled to nine million dollars, and the company's massive expansion into all continents began.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost 40 years in the chief's chair, his son, Thomas Watson Junior, replaced him.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System / 360 series.
The classic "cock" that established the computer standard of that time, called IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold Lenovo's computer production to the Chinese company, but bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and started to fully deal with consulting and high value added services.
