How prices of tours have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
At that time, travel agencies only sold tours to socialist bloc countries in the vast majority, as Western travel was very limited.
Thus, Czech tourists travelled to the sea (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when the possibility of travelling to Yugoslavia was also possible, but then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the age of socialism was that citizens of the Socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovak people) were not allowed to travel individually within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered tours to the West at the time, but it was necessary to wait overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good friends" in the travel agency.
But it wasn't even won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people," who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it was not possible to raise funds (Western currency) to travel to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
However, by far the Czechs most often spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, resulting in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs had purchased and this habit still survives today.
The travel of Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While holidays in GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum by 1989, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible to travel freely to the most popular Croatia for us until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, starting a huge wave of short-stay visits mainly to Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't get enough of the trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for a while.
In Paris, for example, tours of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for the hotel or the guest house.
The typical feature of Czech travel at this time was driving your own food, cans, salami, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists to buy free Western currency after many thousands of years.
However, our standard of living and, with this, our average salaries increased, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Due to increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours regularly since 1997 with charter flights, making air tours incredibly cheaper compared to the past, thanks to the possibility to negotiate quantity discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already had visa-free travel to virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when due to considerable demand it was sent from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exotic, it was to Thailand.
From this year on, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs per year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists, and by doing so, our country has definitely been among the world's most advanced countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and spent more than CZK 15 thousand per person for the first time in history for one foreign holiday including the cost of the place of residence.
