Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book entitled Beauty and Grief: The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War begins with such a long list of performers that your head turns.
One piece of advice on how to behave in that moment: carefully rip this page out and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund's novel story, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a beacon - at times when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it quite well, as "antihistorical work."
It contains several well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, but it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists, and debates on tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, explains the author, as it is a "book about what it was like." It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Grief" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, rescue drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives twinkle like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones join in the mix of fates, while others quench.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classical historical novels.
It edits the idea that World War I was only about the fearsome trenches on the Western front.
"Beauty and Grief" has also skillfully explored other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book solve the problems of falling bee nests, spending Christmas in the shadow of pyramids or facing the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, it's a very moving reading.
War consumes people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina reeking of gunpowder.
When there's a gun fire in the distance and you're a woman who's home with her children, will you run or stay?
Who's coming, anyway?
Almost no one understands what's happening, not even why the whole war has been unleashed.
"The vacuum resulting from the lack of facts," Mr Englund noticed, "was filled with conjecture, supposition, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and Grief" follows stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from biographies, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound terrifying and engaging, but they are absolutely alive and believable thanks to the integration of tiny moments and details.
Many of them talk about suffering and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Replacements everywhere are replaced."
"Coffee substitute, aluminium imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It refers to "meat made from pressed rice cooked in mutton fat (and supplemented with fake bone of wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato husks, shoes with wooden soles'.
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes'.
