Walls have eyes: How scientists study you on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July killing rampage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time on a computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
"We have realised that it is not at all that difficult to get them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of the recently published report by the British Research Team, which concerned European digital populism.
The personal information supply on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says that scientists were enough to simply use the ad on the website to identify, with absolute precision, an idio-demographic group - something that marketing workers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups, and then they focused on them and sent out advertisements. However, instead of inviting them to a newly created group or offering them some dietary products, they called on them to fill out a questionnaire with questions about the level of their education, relation to violence and optimism in relation to their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from over 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without having to leave the office at all.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not as surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are generally young men who are inciting an increasing level of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with off-line activism are more sensible, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything, from health problems to social trends, hidden by stock updates, wall posts, and pressed "I like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users, each providing three different data on average daily basis, making this social network literally "information supernova," which is behind the development of many new research.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"In the past, when you wanted to do a survey of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to a side where they'd never let you go," says Bartlett.
"This all comes down to Facebook - you just go straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken editions on Facebook were much more at risk of the problem of alcoholism than students who kept quiet about the subject.
Moreno proposes that students' peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem cannot be solved if you cannot diagnose it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Centre for the Health, Behavior and Development of Children at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise not have a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly searches its users' data.
The information team developed statistics on the relationship between the relationship status and St. Valentine's Day, voting participation in 2010 and the national satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long claimed that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the site.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"In my opinion, most users did not even think that scientists could look into their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they were concerned, they thought the information was only between them and their friends."
Subsequently, it is also a question of methodology to consider.
Even in off-line research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
