A lie could destroy entire careers and break the stability of many countries.
The New York congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself when he published information that was immediately disproved by undeniable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of using his campaign funds to try to hide his illegitimate affair.
And no one ever forgets the media circus that went around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
It's crawling with stories of cheating in school and college.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many scams are we dealing with?
Studies show that on one day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Let's assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times during the first ten minutes of their first encounter in life.
Determining lies, or "recognizing lies," is an essential skill that should be acquired by everyone, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar to, say, the Sarada, when one says, "I have you." Recognizing deception is a serious science sector working with scientific data collected during the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of research is that most of the old lie myths have been refuted.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're stuttering, stuttering, blushing or twitching.
But don't take it from the fact that it's somehow difficult to spot and detect liars.
A trained lie identifier can detect the truth from a large building, tiny expressions in the face, the way in which questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from an extensive and emerging industry on the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help to you in today's complex world - especially if your duties include hiring, holding interviews, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them relax in vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "aimed at others" - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than free people (but the lies they say are usually "outrageous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's normal behavior.
It's called "initial observation."
Thanks to him, he'll have a later finding out what to compare to.
Notice the subject's posture, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone is patting their feet all the time, so that you don't wrongfully accuse them of lying just because they start patting their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and non-verbal behavior.
But just think of it as a warning signal, not as proof of a lie.
People who are telling a lie can stop moving the upper half of the body when they're trying to remember their imaginary story, the toes of the shoes can turn to the door, lean towards the exit, significantly change the posture or show "relief after the conversation" - excessive cost relief and change of position when there is a difficult confession behind them.
Interview people often give a false signal that the interview is over just to see what relief will look like after it's over.
Feel the subject's language as well.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once misspoke and used the past tense when he claimed his murdered wife was alive, which triggered a nationwide search for her body.
The deceptive individuals can also express themselves in a aloft manner: 'I had no sexual relationship with Mrs Lewinski' or repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are very slight.
Some people can use a lot of "mitigating language" when they answer the difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
In such an answer, we will not know too many facts, and it is often another warning signal.
There is no spell to uncover any lie, but it is possible to acquire skills to spy out a lie.
With these skills, one will have a better chance of not falling for a liar and a cheater in his personal and professional skills.
