Climate failure has hampered the economy
During the first year of the reign of Maria López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability grew in Sinaloa, foreign investment declined, and the economy with them.
The year 2011 will be written into the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, which is called the government of change itself. This government has brought with it great expectations of economic progress, but due to the adverse climate conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth has been recorded and even the main indicators of economic development have fallen.
Low February temperatures have caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the potential for growth of the state economy, led to a 3.6% reduction in economic activity in the first semester of this year. In agriculture, there has been a 31.16% drop, which has undermined the dynamics of other economic sectors as well.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded at 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78,03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were found to be partially damaged.
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state increased during the first three quarters. From January to March 55 053 of the population of the state of Sinaloa was unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4,53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5,28% and between July and August average unemployment increased further and reached 6,19%, representing around 74 000 unemployed people.
Less liquidity
For unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa it is possible to explain the increase in unemployment indirectly, based on the steps taken at the level of public policy, according to Gerard López Cervantes, the Director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences.
"We are witnessing rising unemployment related to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the reduction of resources due to legislation approved by Congress in the context of the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who are illegally possessing dollars to earn, invest or use it."
Stopping migration
López Cervantes said that a demographic factor is also involved in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people leaving for work abroad to the United States has decreased, both because of difficult entry and because, even if these people get abroad, it is hard for them to get a job. Thus, people remain and demand work from our state and thus unemployment is growing," he said.
Unreliability
The labour market analysis in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the increasing unreliability that prevails in terms of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the people employed in the state work without paying benefits to the social security administration.
Other features of the labour market, such as low salaries, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries are from all over the country, as stated by the registries of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Labour and Social Planning Secretariat.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5 352 pesetas until September, well below the national average, which ranges to 7 375 pesetas.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Together with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the most significant decline in foreign direct investment over the last 10 years was recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment amounted to $630 697 between January and June, representing a decrease of $87.74% compared to $5 143 312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the Government of the State indicated investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year, which were mainly directed towards companies in the field of services.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government asked the state Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local Congress approved a loan of 2 600 million peso. By November, no debt gains were recorded in any sector of the state economy.
Reaction
According to representatives of the business sector, Mario López Valdése's first year of government pointed out a lack of governing skills.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Transformation Industry Chamber, stated that in 2011, there was no reconciliation of the will of individual sectors, including the government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small during this year. We need to work intensively to get back the land we lost this year. In 2012 we have to double our efforts, missing harmonisation of the efforts of all of us and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
The slowness of the economy
Loredo López stated that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year had stopped the state economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frost. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough so that it could restore dynamism, which would enable it to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. Therefore, at the end of the year we found ourselves far below the expected forecasts," he said.
Re-definition of the mission
According to Teodor Salazar Uriarte, President of the Labour Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed towards more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we see that it is working. We believe that a long-term plan is needed to redefine the objectives and economic direction of the state, because it is important that all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has is mobilised," he said.
The work ahead of us
President Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, some progress has been made in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
It stated that the current administration has shown progress with regard to the conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that there is a view of the work done here and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work before us," he said.
