The Court approves the "end of analogue broadcasting" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analogous signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) rejected the constitutional action brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the Presidential Decree, which wants to speed up the so-called "switch off of analogous signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. It stated that there were no necessary eight votes to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued a decree stating the steps that would lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed because the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to comment on the constitutionality or inconstitutionality of the said decree, which thus remains valid, were not attained.
The draft judgment drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero provides for the possibility of declaring a decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of all issues relating to radio and television is a matter which, according to the law, is reserved for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), thus violating the principles of hierarchical subordination and the exceptions to the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an effort to combat the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all the actions described therein leading to the transition to digitisation.
The ministerial meeting also decided to reject the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a debate on a proposal which is also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the proposal's arguments in the sense that a federal executive could not structure measures through general standards to prepare public administration.
"I do not think that even if she did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory authority," and recall that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of a federal executive with a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
Replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in years. It relates to better use of radio spectrum, better quality of signal and more channels.
It believes that delaying change would delay the benefits of digitisation, which requires a decision on public interest, because digitisation does not only have a technical dimension, but "also affects economic, social, political and national security issues."
As he pointed out, these questions "require the operation of the entire system in place, in line with the principle of the economic direction of the state. It includes a number of competences entrusted by the Constitution to the government of the state."
He recalled that many countries around the world had already completed the transition to the digital system and did so through their governments, even though they had high-level technical bodies at their disposal.
He stated that it is not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree, which, to some extent, interferes with the powers of Congress, to introduce compliance with the laws of the legislature into the administration.
In Michoacán they analyze the possibility of adding "voice by voice"
According to the data published by the PREP, the difference between the first and second places in the governor's election is less than 27 percent.
The possibility of adding "voice after voice" appeared in this year's election in Michoacán, where, in line with the figures published by the PREP, the difference between the first and second places in the Governor's election is less than 27%, and the 879 votes of the total 6074 constituencies have not yet been counted.
In this context, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute in Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral authority approved a number of measures to harmonise local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán has not officially confirmed its political constitution or its State Electoral Code or the Law on Electoral Justice. The State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal period for their entry into force was due to expire in this parliamentary term and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel has omitted their publication within the prescribed period in the Act of the Official Gazette, with some objections against them.
9 November, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislature and declared the voice of the head of state on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal," because it has no right to "nor approve them nor veto them."
On the question of the possibility of counting "voice after voice" María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the IEM General Council, it would be possible for the local electoral authority to carry out both partial and overall census.
In this way, partial counting of votes, one or more electoral bales, will be possible under the following conditions: voting results do not agree; there is no record of the census and the calculation in the relevant box or is not available to the President; or if errors and obvious violations of election results have occurred.
In addition, the overall recalculation of votes in all ballot boxes will be possible if there is an indication that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; each time an explicit request from the party representative and / or the coalition proposed by the candidate in second place appears at the beginning of the session.
The overall recalculation of the votes will also be possible if, after a proper census, it is found that the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point and whenever there is an explicit request from a political party whose candidate has finished second place, in which case the election packages for which partial census has been made will be eliminated.
It should be noted that in such a situation there are elections in Morelia, where according to PREP the difference between the first and second places is less than 0.16%, although 129 of the 923 constituencies have not yet been counted.
