When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played in a long time, we focus on them, and we're also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
That makes the show more interesting for us, which is why I think it's more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of art.
If you look back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much we have been given and we are moved that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to look at the places we've always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the genre grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which all the great ones are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement comes from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time, a group is created in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We're proud of it, and it's an honor to be part of a group from Seattle.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a long time longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky that we are still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone sufficient freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music, and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word glory was not easy. However, thanks to your success you can do what you like.
How do you balance?
The way we grew up, it became increasingly easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much because it's very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remember that you have to respect the music and what you gave her, and you can't let yourself get carried away by being famous rock stars, and neither one of us has ever really cared about that.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs, and at the beginning it was something spectacular.
We existed as a band for three years, and we never published an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. Most importantly, even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I hear a song or look at pictures, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh, talk about music or football and many others.
She was an incredible person, and we miss her so much.
The Las Robertas National Band will be in charge of starting the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the opening act?
Yes, production sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious about what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter in person?
That's the question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He's singing it, and I think he's adding the first thing he can think of.
Who affects you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
I'm the first to attack Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about the bassist I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge even though he's not in fashion anymore?
I think we've all always felt a little detached from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I think of groups that I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were created at the same time, and if music is still valid today, it's something great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and groups like Mudhoney are playing better music than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly bleak character, and now it's more positive.
What is behind this change?
This is interesting, because I have a feeling that there are a few songs in the new album that are light, but there are also songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and you have some kind of trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or your boyfriend, these things start to affect your art and your music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make dreary music.
