Fujimori has been hospitalized again for medical testing.
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss suffered in the lower extremities, informed his attending physician.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), is suffering from several diseases, including cancer of the tongue, for which he has been operated four times and is under the control of doctors at the moment.
Member Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N television station that Fujimori will be taking tests within three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases, where he should find out why he's hurting and why he's losing his strength in the lower extremities.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself does not want mercy because he feels innocent.
He was operated four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and other diseases like severe erosive gastric disease, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs were added to these problems, by the doctor.
Fujimori has served his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his government.
Mujica visiting Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, headed by the President of Uruguay, José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start a visit to Mexico on Tuesday. Its aim is to achieve an expansion of trade between the two nations and to touch on the political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet her Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón on Wednesday. It is the most important meeting of an extensive visit full of meetings with political, business and representatives of the Uruguya community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan Presidential Office.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political matters between the two countries, "published the Uruguay Presidential Office on its website.
According to the local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France when French President Nicolas Sarkozy placed the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that would continue to remain in the position of tax havens would be excluded from the international community.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world. Since January this year, the Latin American country has concluded an agreement to exchange information to prevent double taxation.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has sought to specify fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the "blacklist" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), on which are countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of tax cooperation.
From a commercial point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have concluded a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has enhanced the exchange of goods between the two countries.
