Colom approved the release of Portilla to the United States
On Tuesday, President Álvaro Colom announced that he had taken steps to release former President Alfonso Portilla, who is to be held accountable in the United States for a conspiracy to launder $70 million.
This is the end of the process aimed at having Guatemala respond at the request of the northern country, which demands the release of Portilla, so that it can be judged.
At the press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was consistent with the independence of the judicial and executive powers and that he had taken note that the criminal court had already ordered extradition.
He assured that, during his mandate, he "did not" interfere "with court decisions and allowed all the editions that came to his desk.
In addition to Portilla, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and serious assault and Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Coloma's move is a step in execution after all judicial and constitutional instances have been exhausted to lead the trial against the former President, who ruled between 2000 and 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be issued once its legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and human rights are respected.
Portillo was found innocent in the matter of embezzlement of $120 million at the Ministry of Defense at the time of his presidency, and this process was preceded by extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and brought the case back into play.
