Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of an accident involving the death of the secretary of the governor, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communication and Transport (SCT) informed that the results of the accident investigation, in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other persons died, show that the helicopter hit the terrain with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt forced landing.
At the press conference Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the aircraft launch, the pilot stated that climate conditions allow flights.
"Parts that appear suggest that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings tangled in a tree branch 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull."
He also reported that the unit was intended for 19 persons and therefore met all requirements for the transfer of personnel.
In addition, it stated that no parts were found on the ground following an investigation carried out in the area of impact.
"In the search it was found that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft hit the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 persons, meeting all requirements for passenger transport.
The terrain shows a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary has assured that the most important thing at the moment is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Managing Director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the President's General Staff was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on a soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that it was a normal overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At the press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome named six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the aviation standards, the flight was conducted according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
The AICM reports indicate adequate launch conditions, according to which the aircraft moves towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds the crew searched for a lower area and greater visibility up to the Cuernavaca Valley.
The location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the helicopter from the radar are consistent; it is likely that there was no loss of control before the impact, nor was there any disruption in the trajectory of the flight.
Distraction of aircraft residues in restricted territory:
The information currently available allows us to assume that the impact has occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A sketch of the diffusion of the remains of the aircraft indicates that at the time of impact on land, the helicopter was solid.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident to suggest that there had been an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the field work, the remains of the aircraft were found up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is levelled, the slope is between seven and 30 degrees.
Photographs show footage likely to break up along that route.
Information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After careful search in the vicinity of the accident, the remains of the helicopter have not been found in a territory that is more extensive than the area of laying, which reinforces the presumption that the impact occurred in a state where the helicopter was still whole.
The Mexican Health Insurance Institute has begun research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect an obesity gene in children and young people. Research called "obesity genetics in children and adolescents" will allow you to obtain results related to overweight.
In a report by the Head of the Research Medical Unit in the field of biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Health Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and students of post-graduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestan) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public may also be involved in the research, with or without authorisation. People can come to participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will be tested by adolescents every Saturday from 8 am.
He stressed that research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (the Mexican State) and since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Zahualcóyolt Sports Centre (the East of the Mexican State).
As soon as the data are obtained from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independent Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research was to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors to Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific dietary questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, girth) are made each Saturday, blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes that are involved in the formation of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health care concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health surveys carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years only boys had an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%. A dramatic increase also occurred in overweight cases' said the IMSS expert.
It stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He informed that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic features, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, obesity genetics are commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, which will determine whether they have any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-coloured wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm suggests that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetic conditions.
For now, the information is confidential, it is transmitted in writing to the parents and is explained by all measurements and changes in the lifestyle that have to be made in order to avoid illness by their children.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day and using means of transport instead of walking a short distance.
Overweight also causes a large calorie intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in the asphalt of UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty of UNAM, creates modified asphalt with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, independent of climate conditions and temperature
If paving was properly taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the metropolitan area of Valle de México, alerted Rafael Herrera Najer, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even it would be possible to completely remove them.
In his lecture, the Technological Causes of Potholes, which he made in the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his leadership develops modified asphalt with polymers, creating a mixture of similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najer believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is the grouping of molecules of hydrocarbons, molecules of great molecular weight, which are called asphaltenes, and others with low molecular weight, which are called maltenes. Together, they provide asphalt with a typical viscosity elastic character.
The Viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it acts as a liquid, at 120 degrees has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, added.
This means that the integrity of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, alerted by an expert in chemical engineering.
A scientist from the Chemical Faculty observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers there is a asphalt insert, made of small pebbles embedded in the asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms a liner is covered with asphalt.
It is thus possible for the forces in the tile to decompose well when driving through cars or when creating pressure.
If it was modified asphalt, it would have decomposed even better, thought a chemical engineer.
He added that on the asphalt insert, the last layer of the mantle, made up of fine stones, was placed with sand also embedded in the asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must provide friction of the road.
As part of the paving will be exposed to heavy loads, the mantle must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken for the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to remember. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is damp, the water spreads in and it's hard to get out, it causes softening of all layers of tiles and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the creation of potholes, the film of the mantle will be first destroyed and then the asphalt liner will be damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one moment, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in the formation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tiles must correspond to the load on vehicles and it must be ensured that the load will not be exceeded. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent formation of potholes.
Rafael Herrera has pointed out that as far as asphalt is concerned, we still have a lot of work to do and research is at the beginning. For example, asphalt emulsions that are already available on the market in other countries and allow for easy repair of potholes without having to use high temperatures.
