Austria
entry of the golden rule on a balanced budget into the Constitution
On Tuesday, the Government of the Great Coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats, in power in Austria, decided to enter the "golden rule" of budgetary policy into the Constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and to avoid a possible reduction in Austria's rating by rating agencies (AAA).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the conclusion of the ministerial meeting in a situation where Austrian public debt, with its 74.6%, is high above the criterion of a maximum of 60% laid down by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than those of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency had been reduced by just one degree from AAA to AA +, we would have had to pay three billion euros more each year in interest," argued Vice-Chancellor and Secretary of State, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is therefore following the request of the Eurozone Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where Heads of State or Government have strongly requested that, by the end of 2012, the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of the balance of public accounts be entered in the Constitution or in the law of the same value.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model," Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule."
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017 onwards the public structural deficit of the federal state may not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the Länder, as well as municipalities, will have to report a balanced budget.
The aim is to put public debt below the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty in the 2020 / 21 horizon.
