Nord Stream, a new Russian gas port to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline directly connecting Eastern Europe to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
They must supply gas equivalent to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, among them four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte, turned together the control wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe each year through the first pipeline of 1 224 km between the region of St Petersburg and the Land of Meckleburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, a quantity equal to the entire French consumption.
And it's already reminded of the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being led around the country by any third State (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries are losing a little bit of power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats to shut down its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
It was most strongly expressed by Warsaw when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact," referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying it's a politically sensitive subject.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created cracks between Europeans from the east and the west.
Russia was only five years ago able to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose deposits are coming to an end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," confirmed François Fillon in the ceremonial opening of this pipeline and demonstrated at what point the large gas contracts of things are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom's leaders present in a large number in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with a concrete casing to protect it from the anchorages of seagoing vessels.
It rests at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
In its construction it was necessary to avoid minefields from World War II.
"For security reasons, almost a hundred must have been removed or destroyed," says Jens Muller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not cut anywhere on its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were very little eager to see Russian state society permanently settled off their shores.
"In the event of a malfunction, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute," Jens Muller states.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline will leak into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely to the contractor, for the welds were designed to cause leakage every 100,000 years.
The external control of the gas pipeline is carried out by an underwater ship-drawn robot, while the interior of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pressurised by gas.
At the end of the 3-day journey at a speed of 3 m / s, it shall provide accurate information on any deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to function for 50 years without the need for any repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains in charge, holding 51%.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each) as well as the Dutch company Gasuni and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream in charge of the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has its registered office in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased this company for five years with a contract that can be renewed, all its gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will benefit from total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," Jens Müller states.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was secured by 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs thus increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will come back to them, because Gazprom is the only one who takes the risk.
The pipeline leaves the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the gas output gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
