Moleskin benefits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases... The brand extends to a variety of carriers.
Success that aroused envy: in autumn 2006 Modo Modo was bought by SG Capital Europe Investment Funds, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why is the proportion of unemployed disabled workers so high?
Around 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today opens on the 15th week for employing handicapped people.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed disabled persons is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the whole population.
Is it depressing?
"No, he underlines Éric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organises the week for employment of handicapped people."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the percentage of the unemployed was not twice, but three times higher."
"Nevertheless, much remains to be done."
It should be said that for unemployed disabled people there are many obstacles to their entry into work.
These are older people: 37% are more than 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% of them are undergraduate and of 2.3 million university students are only 10 000 disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the handicapped compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to employment and which represent the 'core problem', according to Christian Grapin, the Director-General of the Tremplin Association, established in 1992, to help businesses accept handicapped workers.
So much for objective brakes.
It remains unsaid, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slow.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that interrogated managers had a "poor level of knowledge of handicapped persons" with "an exaggerated idea of persons in a driving chair and mental or mental deficiencies."
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the objective of employing 6% of the disabled workers provided for in the 1987 Act.
The latest known figures, which come from 2008, show a figure of 2.6%.
"We are now moving around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, in charge of collecting fees from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence is the number of "fined 'enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59.000 guilty enterprises between 2007 and 2011 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euro).
"The Law of 2005, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large businesses."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
